<table width="600" border="3" cellspacing="02" cellpadding="8" align="center" bgcolor="#dddddd">
  <tr> 
    <td class="font10"  style="font-family: verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif"  >      <div align="center" class="font10">
        <p><span class="font11"><b><font color="#094A66">The 
        Àryabhatiya 
          of &Agrave;ryabhata</font><font color="#094A66">:</font></b></span> 
          <b><font color="#094A66"><span class="font11"> The oldest exact astronomical 
          constant? </span> </font></b></p>
        </div>
      <p><strong><font color="#660000">2012.08.09</font> - </strong> <font color="#000000">In 1997, when this research article was accomplished, formulas for astronomy constants were not as refined as today. Now, given new formulations and  application of the distinction between atomic and ephemeris time, results will be slightly different. Rather than overwrite this step in examination of ancient astronomy, I'm leaving the article intact with the caveat that researchers should utilize the latest methods to examine the questions raised herein and should expect  new results to vary. For the latest astronomical constant formulas and applet downloads, go to my <a href="index.html">Astronomy Pages</a>.</font></font></p>
      <p align="center"><img src="../images/bar-gb.gif" border="1"
naturalsizeflag="0" align="BOTTOM" vspace="4" width="478" height="6" /><br />
<em><strong><font color="#094A66">The 
        Àryabhatiya 
          of &Agrave;ryabhata: The oldest exact astronomical 
      constant? </span> </font></strong></em><br />&copy;1997 by James Q. Jacobs. All rights reserved.</font><font></p>
      <p><font color="#000000">In the work <i>The Àryabhatiya of 
        &Agrave;ryabhata, An Ancient Indian Work on Mathematics and Astronomy, </i>translated by William Eugene Clark, Professor of Sanskrit at Harvard 
        University (The University of Chicago Press, Chicago, Illinois. 1930), 
        I found the following to be written:</font>
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <table width="480" border="0" cellspacing="2" cellpadding="10">
          <tr>
            <td bgcolor="#cccccc" class="font10"><font color="#000000">"In a yuga the revolutions of the Sun are 4,320,000,
                of the Moon 57,753,336, of the Earth eastward 1,582,237,500, of Saturn
            146,564, of Jupiter 364,224, of Mars 2,296,824 . . . " (page 9).</font></td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </blockquote>
      <font color="#000000">As can be seen from the Clark translation &Agrave;ryabhata
       wrote that 1,582,237,500 rotations of the Earth equal 57,753,336 lunar orbits.
       (These same two numbers are also presented by G. R. Kay in his appendices,
       where they are attributed to &Agrave;ryabhata and Pus&iacute;la.) This is
        an extremely accurate ratio for two fundamental cosmic motions (1,582,237,500
        / 57,753,336 = <b><font color="#990000">27.3964693572</font></b>).</font>      <p class="font10"><font color="#000000">Given
          Jan. 1, 2000 astronomical constants and given  the present day formulas
          to temporally adjust the astronomical constants,  I calculated that &Agrave;ryabhata's
          ratio was exact for 1604 BC.* The  resulting data is presented in Table
          1. The temporal variation formulas  used can be obtained from my <a href="astrofor.html">Astronomy
          Formulas</a> 
        page. The date AD 500 is the approximate epoch in which &Agrave;ryabhata
         wrote. &Agrave;ryabhata was born in 476 in Patna, India and died in 550.
          His Àryabhatiya was probably written in A.D 498.</font> 
        His sources remain obscure.
        <br />
&nbsp;        
      </p><center class="font10">
        <table width="536" border=1 cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 bgcolor="#C0C0C0" >
          <tr align=CENTER valign=CENTER> 
            <td style="font-family: verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif"  align=CENTER valign=CENTER colspan="4"> 
              <div align="center" class="font10">Table 1. Comparison of <font color="#000000"><i>The 
                Àryabhatiya of &Agrave;ryabhata</i></font> and Astronomic 
                values.</div>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr align=CENTER valign=CENTER class="font10"> 
